    <Documents>
        <Document ID="353BA134-8841-4A50-82E6-978DA95761B4">
            <Title>synthesis + search</Title>
            <Text>To power retrieval and citations:
	•	Parse each document into chunks (page/section level).
	•	Store:
	◦	chunk text (encrypted)
	◦	chunk metadata (non-sensitive minimal metadata, also preferably encrypted)
	◦	hash/provenance pointers to raw doc + page range
Embeddings / semantic index options
	•	Option 1 (privacy-max): embeddings generated and stored on-device; cloud only syncs encrypted index.
	•	Option 2 (balanced): embeddings generated in cloud inside your secure compute boundary; store embeddings encrypted at rest.
	•	Option 3 (simple): store embeddings plaintext in cloud (not ideal for PHI).
I’d aim for Option 1 or 2.
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="EB44C9AF-0096-4C82-A421-F0E49E8EA86A">
            <Text>Implementing multi-prong approach with record ingest meta-tagging, including: 

What Local Can Do Well:
Field
Method
Accuracy
Dates
Regex + NaturalLanguage
~90%
Phone/Fax
Regex
~95%
Provider names
"Dr." / "MD" / "NP" patterns
~70%
Facility names
NER (organization entities)
~60%
MRN/Account #
Regex patterns
~85%
What Local Struggles With:
	•	Document type classification (is this a lab result or a radiology report?)
	•	Distinguishing "report date" vs "visit date" vs "printed date"
	•	Understanding context ("Quest Diagnostics" = lab facility)
	•	Extracting provider specialty
	•	Handling varied layouts
Hybrid Approach (Recommended):


┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Layer 1: Local (instant, always runs)      │
│  - Regex: dates, phones, MRN, SSN           │
│  - NLP NER: names, organizations            │
│  - Keywords: "Lab Results" → labResults     │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                    ↓
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Layer 2: On-Device AI (iOS 26+)            │
│  - Apple Foundation Models                   │
│  - Runs locally, no network                 │
│  - Better context understanding             │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                    ↓
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Layer 3: Cloud AI (optional, user-invoked) │
│  - "Smart Fill" button                      │
│  - Uses your existing anonymization         │
│  - Most accurate, handles edge cases        │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────┘
My recommendation: Start with Layer 1 (local regex + Apple NaturalLanguage NER) — it's free, fast, and gets you 70% there. You already have the anonymization pipeline for Layer 3 when you want it.
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="F57C7EC8-D905-40A7-AE0C-249DA92390EE">
            <Title>13. Phase 1 POC</Title>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="D494A3CD-BD2B-438B-B062-5ADB72D917EB">
            <Title>Legal</Title>
            <Text>1) Language discipline
	•	“For informational use”
	•	“Patient-managed”
	•	“Not a medical record”
	•	“Not intended for diagnosis or treatment”
Boring but legally powerful.
2) Provenance &amp; citation everywhere
	•	Every AI summary links to source documents
	•	Clear “derived vs original” labeling
	•	No black-box conclusions
This reinforces “assistive, not authoritative.”

3) Export, don’t integrate
	•	PDF summaries
	•	Human-readable timelines
	•	No write-back into EHRs
	•	No HL7/FHIR ingestion into provider systems unless HIPAA-ready
4) User-mediated sharing
	•	Patient initiates sharing
	•	Time-limited access
	•	View-only
	•	No clinician accounts by default
This keeps control with the individual.
5) Clear product posture
You’re a personal organizer, not a clinical system.
The moment you:
	•	Sell to hospitals
	•	Add clinician dashboards
	•	Automate care workflows
…you should flip to HIPAA mode intentionally.
Important nuance
A clinician choosing to trust a patient’s personal record does not automatically impose HIPAA obligations on you.
HIPAA attaches through:
	•	Contractual relationships
	•	Operational reliance
	•	Delegated functions
Not casual use.

Practical guidance for your hybrid architecture
If you expect this edge case (and you should):
	•	Keep cloud AI outputs clearly labeled “informational”
	•	Require explicit patient consent for sharing
	•	Make clinician access read-only and ephemeral
	•	Never store clinician notes or decisions
	•	Avoid anything that looks like clinical decision support
One-line takeaway
Clinicians informally leaning on patient-managed records is common and acceptable; it becomes a HIPAA issue only when your system starts acting for clinicians rather than for patients.
If you want, next we can:
	•	Draft product language that holds this boundary
	•	Design a “HIPAA switch” architecture for future expansion
	•	Map edge-case risk to concrete mitigations (table format)

Three common real-world scenarios (and how they’re treated)
1) Patient shows records during a visit
Example
	•	Patient opens an app or PDF
	•	Doctor glances at lab history or timeline
	•	Uses it as context while still relying on their own EHR
HIPAA impact
	•	Your product remains consumer-only
	•	Clinician is viewing patient-provided information
	•	No BA relationship
	•	No HIPAA obligation for your platform
This is very common and generally safe.

2) Clinician “leans on it” informally
Example
	•	Doctor says: “This timeline is helpful”
	•	Uses it to ask better questions
	•	Does not import it into their EHR
	•	Does not depend on it as authoritative
HIPAA impact
	•	Still consumer-only
	•	Clinician judgment remains primary
	•	Your system is contextual, not authoritative
This is the gray-but-accepted zone.

3) Clinician relies on it operationally (danger zone)
Example
	•	Clinician documents decisions based on your app’s summaries
	•	Uses it as the primary longitudinal record
	•	Imports structured data directly into EHR
	•	Tells patient “this is your official record”
	•	Clinic instructs patients to use your system
HIPAA impact 🚨 You are likely now a business associate
	•	You’re supporting clinical decision-making
	•	Covered entity reliance is present
	•	HIPAA obligations attach (BAA, audits, safeguards)
This is where platforms accidentally cross the line.

What regulators look for
They evaluate signals, not single events:
	•	Is the product marketed to clinicians?
	•	Is there bidirectional EHR integration?
	•	Are clinicians encouraged to rely on outputs?
	•	Are summaries framed as clinical or diagnostic?
	•	Does the system replace or supplement EHR workflows?
	•	Are providers contractually involved?
If the answers tilt “yes,” you’re moving into HIPAA land.
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="2878DE26-FC88-402B-BE83-673E20ADF64A">
            <Text>Phase 1: Local-First PHR + Minimal LLM Integration (POC)
Goal
Prove that a user can:
	1	Store personal health records locally
	2	Ask natural-language questions about them
	3	Get useful synthesized responses from an LLM
	4	With clear boundaries around privacy and scope
Not to be HIPAA-ready. Not to scale. Not to impress compliance officers.
Just: does the thing work?

Core assumptions
	•	Single user
	•	Single device
	•	No multi-device sync
	•	No provider integration
	•	Consumer-only posture
	•	Plain-text documents only

What Phase 1 includes (and nothing more)
1) Local document store
	•	Folder-based or lightweight local database
	•	Plain-text files only (.txt, .md)
	•	Each document is:
	◦	One record (visit note, lab summary, discharge note, etc.)
	◦	User-imported or pasted
Example structure:

/records/
  2023-06-14_primary_care_visit.txt
  2023-08-02_lab_results.txt
  meds_current.txt
No PDFs. No OCR. No parsing. No FHIR.

2) Minimal metadata
Each document gets:
	•	Title
	•	Date (manual or filename-derived)
	•	Optional tags
Store this in:
	•	A simple JSON file or SQLite table
Example:

{
  "id": "doc_001",
  "title": "Primary care visit",
  "date": "2023-06-14",
  "tags": ["primary care"]
}

3) Naive chunking
	•	Split documents into fixed-size chunks (e.g., 500–800 tokens)
	•	Keep:
	◦	chunk_id
	◦	document_id
	◦	chunk_text
No embeddings yet. No semantic index.

4) Basic retrieval (dumb but effective)
For a user question:
	•	Load all documents or
	•	Load documents filtered by date or tag
Yes, this is inefficient. That’s fine for Phase 1.

5) Minimal LLM integration
Use a single LLM API call.
Prompt structure:

System:
You are helping a person understand their own medical records.
Do not give medical advice.
Summarize and explain only what appears in the provided text.

User:
Here is my question:
&lt;question&gt;

Here are my personal health records:
&lt;concatenated_chunks&gt;
That’s it.
No RAG framework. No agents. No tools. No memory.

6) Output rules
	•	Plain-text response
	•	No diagnosis
	•	No recommendations
	•	No hallucinated facts
	•	Explicit disclaimer line at the end: “This is informational only and based solely on the provided records.”

7) Simple UI (or CLI)
Anything that lets you:
	•	Add a text file
	•	List documents
	•	Ask a question
	•	See the answer
Examples:
	•	Minimal web UI (React + textarea)
	•	Desktop app shell
	•	CLI script
UI does not matter in Phase 1.

What Phase 1 explicitly does NOT include
This is important.
	•	No encryption
	•	No cloud sync
	•	No embeddings
	•	No vector DB
	•	No multi-user
	•	No auth system
	•	No provider sharing
	•	No OCR
	•	No PDF support
	•	No structured medical models
	•	No compliance claims
If you add these now, you slow yourself down.

What this proves
If Phase 1 works, you’ve proven:
	•	People can meaningfully query their own records
	•	LLMs add real value over raw documents
	•	The synthesis layer is useful
	•	The consumer-only model is viable
	•	The core UX loop is sound
That’s the hard part.
Everything else is engineering.

What to look for during testing
You’re not testing performance. You’re testing utility.
Ask:
	•	Does this reduce cognitive load?
	•	Does it surface things I’d miss?
	•	Does it help me prepare for a doctor visit?
	•	Does it feel trustworthy?
	•	Where does it hallucinate or confuse context?
These answers guide Phase 2.

Phase 1 → Phase 2 natural evolution
Only after Phase 1 works do you add:
	•	Encryption
	•	Cloud sync
	•	Chunk-level retrieval
	•	Embeddings
	•	Redaction
	•	Consent controls
But Phase 1 should stand alone.

One-sentence Phase 1 summary
A single-user, local, plain-text personal health record store with a direct LLM prompt that can answer questions using only the user’s documents.
If you want next, I can:
	•	Write the exact Phase 1 prompt
	•	Sketch a file layout + pseudocode
	•	Help you choose the least annoying LLM for this use case
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="818B4414-E6DA-4693-85DE-369D94B4DF47">
            <Title>9. User controls</Title>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="44709B0F-E0E1-4080-AAB1-C1D06F2436DA">
            <Title>1. Data Model</Title>
            <Text>Data model: store “raw,” plus an “AI-ready” layer
Raw records (immutable source of truth)
	•	PDFs, CCDA/CCD, FHIR JSON, lab results, imaging reports, visit notes, invoices.
	•	Keep originals intact for legal/medical fidelity.
Normalized layer (structured)
	•	Parse into FHIR-like objects (even if you don’t fully implement FHIR): Medications, Problems, Allergies, Labs, Encounters, Immunizations.
	•	This powers reliable search, timelines, and alerts.
Derived AI layer (non-authoritative)
	•	Summaries, extracted entities, timelines, “questions to ask your doctor,” etc.
	•	Always label as derived; keep provenance pointers back to raw sources.
</Text>
        </Document>
