        <Document ID="AB1D41C1-46BB-4EA6-8E0F-07C342159A7C">
            <Title>Deletions</Title>
            <Text>On the deleted folder — soft delete with 30-day retention is the right pattern. Flag records as deleted with a timestamp, filter them from normal views, and purge after 30 days. We'll build that in a future sprint.

</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="F812CA49-DF24-4982-91D4-B5E7CA86CCFF">
            <Title>1. Storage</Title>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="057C63BA-4FA3-4EA6-8FE4-F61778E38DB1">
            <Text>“Minimum viable” implementation plan (so it ships)
Phase 1
	•	Encrypted local vault
	•	Encrypted cloud sync (raw + metadata)
	•	Full-text search local
	•	Cloud LLM gateway with RAG over a limited set of chunk types
Phase 2
	•	Normalized health graph + timeline UI
	•	Embeddings index (local or secure cloud)
	•	Redaction mode + per-record consent
Phase 3
	•	Provider export packs, audit trails, advanced trend analysis
	•	Confidential compute / stronger isolation if needed
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="75BCFFAF-6941-4287-BB8B-7A8D072FFE3D">
            <Text>User controls (these matter as much as crypto)
Make these first-class:
	•	“Store on device only” per record
	•	“Allow cloud sync” per record
	•	“Allow AI processing” per record (and per category: labs vs notes)
	•	“Redact before AI” toggle
	•	“Offline mode” toggle (local LLM only)
This gives the user meaningful boundaries.
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="2ED58F03-038B-4766-92EF-32F9F70AF928">
            <Text>1) Data minimization first
Before you even redact, ask: do you need to send this at all?
	•	Send only the excerpt needed for the task (not the whole record).
	•	Prefer summaries you generate locally (or with a non-sensitive pass) over raw documents.
	•	Avoid sending attachments, filenames, provider names, MRNs, exact dates, phone numbers, emails, addresses, screenshots, full PDFs, etc.
Practical pattern: “smallest necessary context” + “short retention.”
2) On-device redaction and normalization
Do a privacy pass on-device before the network call.
Redact or generalize common identifiers:
	•	Names, emails, phones, addresses
	•	Medical record numbers, account IDs, insurance IDs
	•	Full dates (convert to month/year or relative time like “3 months ago”)
	•	Locations (convert ZIP to 3-digit ZIP region or county, or remove entirely)
	•	Free-text that includes “my wife Betsy” type relationships, employers, schools, etc.
Replace with consistent placeholders so the model can still reason:
	•	NAME_1, CLINIC_1, MEDICATION_1, DATE_1
If you need continuity across a single conversation, keep the mapping in-memory on device for that session only, then discard it.
Important reality: perfect anonymization of free text is hard. Treat it as “risk reduction,” not a guarantee.
3) Pseudonymization for app-level linking (not identity)
If you need to associate requests with a user for rate-limits or quotas, do it without sending user identity to the AI provider.
	•	Use a random app-scoped UUID that never leaves your system as “real identity.”
	•	If you must send an identifier at all, send a rotating, short-lived pseudonymous token (daily or per-session), not a stable user ID.
	•	Do not hash emails/phones and call it anonymous. Hashes are reversible by dictionary attack if the input space is guessable.
4) Strip metadata you do not control on-device (use a relay)
If your iPhone app calls an AI provider directly, the provider will still see metadata like IP address, timing, user agent-ish details, and your API key must live in the app (bad idea).
For most serious privacy goals, use a minimal backend “relay”:
	•	App sends redacted text to your relay over TLS
	•	Relay removes or avoids logging payloads
	•	Relay calls the AI API server-to-server
	•	Relay returns the response
This helps with:
	•	Hiding user IP from the AI provider
	•	Keeping API keys off the device
	•	Centralized policy enforcement (redaction rules, allow-lists, rate limits)
	•	Auditing without storing sensitive content
5) Do not store sensitive prompts or outputs in logs
This is where privacy often fails.
	•	Disable request/response body logging in production (client and server).
	•	Ensure crash reporting tools are not capturing prompts (Sentry, Firebase Crashlytics, OSLog).
	•	If you need analytics, collect only aggregate counters (token counts, latency buckets, feature usage), not text.
6) Encrypt, segment, and expire
Even if you redact, assume residual sensitivity exists.
	•	Encrypt in transit (TLS) and at rest (Keychain, file protection classes).
	•	Segment data by record and by session.
	•	Use short-lived identifiers and expiring caches.
	•	If you store conversation history, give users a “delete” control and honor it.
7) Protect against “linkage attacks”
Even “anonymous” fields can re-identify when combined (classic example: age + ZIP + rare condition).
So generalize:
	•	Age → range (20–29, 30–39)
	•	ZIP → 3-digit ZIP or remove
	•	Dates → relative or month/year
	•	Rare events → consider suppressing details unless needed
8) Give the user an explicit control surface
Especially for a health-record context:
	•	“Send to AI” should be a deliberate action with a clear preview.
	•	Show the exact redacted text that will be sent.
	•	Provide toggles like:
	◦	Include dates: Off by default
	◦	Include location: Off by default
	◦	Include medications: On, but redacted brand names if needed
	•	“Local-only mode” for users who never want cloud AI.
9) Choose an AI mode that matches the privacy bar
You have three broad options:
	1	On-device model (best privacy, harder engineering, weaker capability depending on model)
	2	Private cloud with strong controls (relay + minimal logs + contractual terms)
	3	Direct-to-provider (fastest to build, hardest to truly anonymize)
For a consumer health records app, a relay is usually the minimum serious baseline.
10) What this looks like as a simple implementation plan
	•	Client
	◦	Build a “privacy scrubber” that transforms text → redacted text
	◦	Show a preview of redacted text
	◦	Send only redacted text + ephemeral session token to your relay
	•	Relay
	◦	Validate request shape, block disallowed fields
	◦	Do not log bodies
	◦	Call AI provider with your server-held API key
	◦	Return response
	•	Storage
	◦	Store only what you must (and ideally store redacted versions)
	◦	Expire anything AI-related quickly unless user explicitly saves it
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="F444A027-A9AC-418D-B1CE-05A3F8EB0403">
