        </Document>
        <Document ID="A720C941-C8A9-45EB-BE93-7AA924297167">
            <Title>Obfuscate API</Title>
            <Text>Do not do this
	•		•	Put OPENAI_API_KEY (or Azure key) in the app bundle, plist, or source.
	•	Even if “obfuscated,” it will be extracted.
Do this instead
iPhone app → Your backend → OpenAI/Azure
	•	Backend can be: Cloudflare Workers, Vercel/Netlify functions, AWS Lambda, Firebase Functions, etc.
	•	Your backend adds:
	◦	rate limiting
	◦	abuse prevention
	◦	user auth (Sign in with Apple, etc.)
	◦	logging and spend controls
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="30847531-EAEC-49C0-8329-430F97EEB309">
            <Title>Derived / synthesized layer</Title>
            <Text>Summaries, timelines, “key takeaways,” topic collections.
Can exist locally, cloud, or both.
Always points back to source docs/chunks.
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="9FD22654-9853-4ACF-BC28-77392F975AD3">
            <Title>3. Security</Title>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="3F5C4855-BB2C-4938-85C3-1C09A774B685">
            <Title>Normalized “health graph”</Title>
            <Text>A structured model (FHIR-ish) for meds, problems, labs, encounters.
Lives locally; cloud has a synced copy (also encrypted / access-controlled).
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="D2B74D70-4358-44E6-83D9-5BF80ABB511A">
            <Text>Option C: “Other” APIs (if you want alternatives)
If you mean “a real LLM API provider besides OpenAI/Azure,” common choices are:
	•	Anthropic (Claude)
	•	Google (Gemini)
	•	AWS Bedrock (multiple models)
	•	Groq (fast inference for some open models)
	•	Together / Fireworks / Replicate (open-model hosting)
If your main requirement is “ship an iPhone app safely + reliably,” the architecture advice below stays the same.
The iOS-safe architecture (what Apple reviewers and attackers both expect)
Do not do this
	•		•	Put OPENAI_API_KEY (or Azure key) in the app bundle, plist, or source.
	•	Even if “obfuscated,” it will be extracted.
Do this instead
iPhone app → Your backend → OpenAI/Azure
	•	Backend can be: Cloudflare Workers, Vercel/Netlify functions, AWS Lambda, Firebase Functions, etc.
	•	Your backend adds:
	◦	rate limiting
	◦	abuse prevention
	◦	user auth (Sign in with Apple, etc.)
	◦	logging and spend controls
Apple policy / UX note
Apple’s HIG for generative AI emphasizes transparency about data use and user expectations; this is especially relevant if you send user text off-device. 

Quick “which should I pick?”
	•		•	OpenAI API: fastest setup, clean docs, straightforward.
	•	Azure OpenAI: best if you’re already in Azure, need enterprise controls, private networking, or org procurement wants Microsoft billing.

If you tell me 2 things, I’ll recommend an exact setup (and a starter snippet)
	1		1	Are you doing text chat only, or also voice / realtime?
	2	Do you already have a backend (AWS/Firebase/etc.), or do you want serverless?
(Meanwhile, if you just want to start today: pick OpenAI API + a tiny serverless proxy. That’s the quickest path to a “real API” in an iPhone app.)
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="5E5DB7EB-0C3B-416C-BA59-685852258730">
            <Title>Cloud Vault</Title>
            <Text>Cloud vault is an encrypted sync + compute adjunct (backup, multi-device, heavy lifting).</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="57C6FFD5-3BAB-4464-B11F-0E4FC19E0728">
            <Text>Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG): keep prompts small and auditable
Instead of sending the entire record set:
Pipeline
	1	User asks a question
	2	Local (or secure server) retrieval pulls top relevant chunks
	3	Only those chunks (minimal necessary) are sent to the LLM
	4	Response includes citations (links back to exact source docs/pages)
Why it matters
	•	Minimizes PHI exposure
	•	Makes answers defensible (especially in healthcare)
	•	Helps you implement “right to be forgotten” because derived content can be recomputed
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="FD0B8079-FBC6-44D6-B488-84598EC552F9">
            <Title>No internet / NO AI functionality</Title>
            <Text>Dummy- local only mode</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="DC876AF2-8BA6-4261-A519-B0960205FEE4">
            <Title>Compliance</Title>
            <Text>Need:
1. Full enterprise SOC 2
2. Full HIPAA compliance stack
3. Mature security operations
We are architected for HIPAA readiness, and here’s our compliance plan.


Sending PHI to an LLM vendor → That vendor must be a Business Associate and sign a BAA.
	A BAA is a Business Associate Agreement.
	It is a legally binding contract required under HIPAA when a company (like your app or a vendor you use) 	handles Protected Health Information (PHI) on behalf of a covered healthcare entity

Could an LLM Be Technically HIPAA-Capable?
Yes.
An LLM platform could be built with:
	•	Encryption at rest
	•	TLS in transit
	•	Access controls
	•	Audit logging
	•	Data retention controls
	•	Dedicated infrastructure
	•	No training on customer data
	•	Regional isolation
	•	Signed BAAs
That would support HIPAA-compliant usage.
Some enterprise cloud AI offerings are structured this way.
But the critical piece is: They must contractually accept HIPAA obligations via a BAA.
HIPAA Safe Harbor requires removing 18 specific identifiers, including:
	•	Names
	•	Geographic subdivisions smaller than a state
	•	All dates (except year)
	•	Phone numbers
	•	Email
	•	SSN
	•	Medical record numbers
	•	Biometric identifiers
	•	Full face photos
	•	Any other unique identifying number or characteristic

HIPAA (United States)
The Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act governs protected health information (PHI) in the US. It has two main rules: the Privacy Rule, which controls how PHI can be used and disclosed, and the Security Rule, which mandates administrative, physical, and technical safeguards for electronic PHI. HIPAA applies to "covered entities" (healthcare providers, insurers, clearinghouses) and their business associates. There's no formal "HIPAA certification" from the government—compliance is self-assessed and enforced through audits and penalties by the Office for Civil Rights.
European Data Compliance
GDPR (General Data Protection Regulation) is the overarching framework for all personal data in the EU/EEA. It emphasizes consent, data minimization, the right to erasure, and data portability. For healthcare specifically, GDPR classifies health data as a "special category" requiring additional protections. Organizations must appoint Data Protection Officers and conduct Data Protection Impact Assessments for high-risk processing. Fines can reach 4% of global annual revenue.
Some EU countries layer additional health-specific regulations on top of GDPR—France has requirements through CNIL, Germany has federal and state-level health data laws, etc.
Healthcare-Specific Certifications and Standards
HITRUST CSF is probably the most recognized certification in US healthcare. It's a certifiable framework that harmonizes requirements from HIPAA, NIST, ISO, and other standards into a single assessment. Many healthcare organizations require HITRUST certification from their vendors.
SOC 2 (Service Organization Control 2) isn't healthcare-specific but is widely used by health tech companies. It audits controls around security, availability, processing integrity, confidentiality, and privacy. A SOC 2 Type II report demonstrates that controls were operating effectively over time.
ISO 27001 is the international standard for information security management systems. It's not healthcare-specific but provides a rigorous framework that many healthcare organizations use as a foundation, sometimes alongside healthcare-specific certifications.
ISO 27799 specifically provides guidance on implementing ISO 27001 within healthcare environments, addressing the unique requirements of health informatics.
Other Notable Frameworks
NIST Cybersecurity Framework is often referenced by US healthcare organizations as a security baseline. FedRAMPmatters if you're working with US government healthcare programs. In the UK, NHS Data Security and Protection Toolkit is required for organizations handling NHS data.

The practical reality is that most healthcare technology companies pursue a combination—typically HITRUST or SOC 2 as a baseline certification, HIPAA compliance documentation, and GDPR compliance if serving European markets. The trend has been toward HITRUST because it maps across multiple frameworks and reduces audit fatigue.
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="02B80B3D-4004-415E-B279-698B60512F1A">
            <Title>Synthesis</Title>
            <Text>Synthesis (summaries/timelines/insights) is treated as derived data that can be regenerated.</Text>
            <Comments>Clarify?</Comments>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="156EF6D5-DD28-480F-98E7-8EF6D7DB978E">
            <Title>Broad Strokes</Title>
            <Text>A “broad strokes” reference architecture
Mobile App
	•	Encrypted vault (raw + normalized + derived)
	•	Local search + optional local embeddings
	•	Redaction module
	•	Key management + biometric unlock
	•	Consent + privacy controls UI
Cloud
	•	Encrypted object storage (records)
	•	Encrypted database (metadata, indexes if you must—prefer local)
	•	Key service (HSM/KMS, split-key workflows, device enrollment)
	•	Audit/event service (privacy-preserving logs: who accessed what, not the content)
AI Layer
	•	Retrieval service (local-first, fallback cloud)
	•	LLM gateway (policy enforcement)
	◦	PII/PHI detectors
	◦	Prompt scrubbing
	◦	Rate limits
	◦	Tenant isolation
	◦	“No training/no retention” enforcement (contract + tech)
	•	Optional: model hosting (your own weights) inside your VPC
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="2F16C935-DCBE-4A27-A885-E3E181107919">
            <Title>Storage</Title>
            <Text>Two copies, one source of truth, and clear rules:
	•	Local vault is the user’s primary workspace (fast, offline, private).
	•	Cloud vault is an encrypted sync + compute adjunct (backup, multi-device, heavy lifting).
	•	Synthesis (summaries/timelines/insights) is treated as derived data that can be regenerated.
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="665D7282-58C6-460F-8A37-E0058DDBF701">
            <Text>Security and privacy controls you’ll want (even in consumer mode)
	•	E2EE for stored data (client-side encryption)
	•	Least-privilege access everywhere (service roles, scoped tokens)
	•	No plaintext logs (ever)
	•	Short retention for transient AI requests (minutes, not days)
	•	User consent controls
	◦	Per-document permission to use in AI
	◦	“Never send to cloud” toggle
	◦	“Only redact mode” toggle
	•	Data deletion
	◦	Delete raw, derived, and indexes
	◦	Cryptographic erasure (destroy keys) as a fast “nuke switch”
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="B399772B-884B-4CC7-BBFE-C0713B70AE42">
            <Title>7. Synthesis</Title>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="92094528-75A3-463B-97EC-C52AA0505F04">
            <Title>2. On-device storage</Title>
            <Text>On-device storage (primary privacy anchor)
On-device vault
	•	Encrypt everything at rest with a vault key stored in:
	◦	iOS: Keychain + Secure Enclave
	◦	Android: Keystore / StrongBox if available
	•	Optional: user unlocks with biometrics + passcode.
On-device indexing
	•	Full-text index (local) for PDFs/text.
	•	Embedding index (local) for semantic search (optional but powerful).
On-device LLM option (good fallback)
	•	For some tasks, run a small local model for:
	◦	Quick Q&amp;A over a single document
	◦	Redaction
	◦	Lightweight summarization
	•	Keeps “no cloud” mode viable.
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="54762E06-D746-4E90-91AA-3455FD9C9549">
            <Title>Summary visit prep</Title>
            <Text>RecordHealth App store QR code in bottom</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="C1ECFE2B-41CE-4712-8DBC-ED21924B0AC1">
            <Title>12. Costs</Title>
            <Text>Quick cost intuition (very rough, but useful)
	•	On-device heavy (local storage/index + occasional cloud LLM): cheapest cloud bill, best privacy.
	•	Cloud RAG + private LLM gateway: moderate cost (you’re paying for secure infra + ops).
	•	Full private model hosting (GPU always-on): most expensive, only worth it at scale or high sensitivity.
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="9D66D50A-5FA0-4073-A43C-39D591926632">
            <Text>Concrete end-to-end flows
Upload / import
	1	User imports PDF/CCDA/FHIR → device
	2	Device encrypts raw + parses to chunks
	3	Device writes local indexes
	4	If sync enabled:
	◦	uploads encrypted raw + encrypted chunks + event log updates
Ask a question (cloud synthesis path)
	1	User question → app
	2	App sends query to gateway (no docs yet, or only a minimal query embedding)
	3	Gateway retrieves relevant encrypted chunks (from cloud vault)
	4	Gateway decrypts inside secure compute boundary (per policy)
	5	LLM call with minimal context
	6	Response + citations returned
	7	Derived artifacts saved back (encrypted) and synced to devices
Multi-device
	•	New phone signs in → device enrollment
	•	Key unwrap flow (split-key) grants access
	•	Device downloads encrypted vault + replays events
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="687D79B0-9319-4754-B3BF-8DC17DEC9C91">
            <Title>Security Gameplan</Title>
            <Text>There are three tiers of encryption on iOS, and they stack:
Tier 1 — iOS Data Protection (do this now, it's free). Set NSFileProtectionComplete on your records directory. The OS encrypts every file at rest using the device passcode and Secure Enclave. Files are unreadable when the device is locked. Zero code changes to your read/write logic, zero processing overhead, and it's what Apple recommends for health data. This alone is legally meaningful — it's hardware-backed AES-256.
Tier 2 — Keychain for secrets + encrypted index (do this now, small effort). You're already using Keychain for the API key. Move any sensitive metadata (patient names, record titles) in index.json to an encrypted blob using CryptoKit's AES.GCM with a key stored in the Keychain. The record files themselves are already protected by Tier 1. This gives you field-level protection for the metadata that ties records to real people.
Tier 3 — Full record-level encryption with CryptoKit (defer to later). Encrypt each record's content with its own key, wrap those keys with a master key in Keychain/Secure Enclave. This is the HIPAA/NIST-grade approach but it changes your entire read/write pipeline and makes debugging much harder. Save this for when your data model is stable.
So concretely for this sprint, the work would be:
	1	Set file protection on the Documents/records directory (5 lines of code)
	2	Create a small EncryptionService using CryptoKit for the index
	3	Wrap your existing index.json read/write in encrypt/decrypt calls
	4	Document the encryption architecture for future HIPAA audit trail
This gives you a defensible encryption posture now without slowing down feature development. When you're ready for Tier 3 later, the EncryptionService is already there — you just expand its scope.
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="ECC4F779-D1BC-44C7-B9ED-E436D1E3F5F4">
            <Title>Voice recording</Title>
            <Text>Whisper API — much better accuracy, but requires sending audio to server
Audio file storage — keep the original recording alongside transcript for reference
Manual editing — let user correct transcript before saving
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="493495E8-61D5-4784-9365-AEA699E2D609">
            <Title>Local Vault</Title>
            <Text>Local vault is the user’s primary workspace (fast, offline, private).</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="1091E117-C3F1-4927-A0D9-C70570A3C9B4">
            <Title>11. Viable Ship plan</Title>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="49DAD835-19CE-49EE-A917-FAB3EC1556BC">
            <Text>The secure cloud “LLM gateway” (your control plane)
This is the part that makes it credibly private:
Gateway responsibilities
	•	Receives user query + retrieves minimal necessary chunks
	•	Enforces user consent rules (which records are allowed for AI)
	•	Redacts if user selects “redaction-only mode”
	•	Sends context to:
	◦	a private managed LLM endpoint, or
	◦	a model you host inside your VPC
	•	Returns response with citations to chunks/pages
	•	Writes derived artifacts (summary objects) back into derived layer
Hard rules
	•	No training on customer data
	•	No persistent prompt logging (or heavily redacted logs only)
	•	Short TTL for transient data
	•	Tenant isolation + per-tenant encryption keys
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="2AB2963F-5701-4659-BC52-10DA92EC53A2">
            <Title>Note tagging</Title>
            <Text>Be able to add notes / corrections</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="B651C68B-4ED1-4EB4-A3BC-B40F977C1B42">
            <Title>Record Health QR code share</Title>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="BF50199C-BF97-4896-ACFC-2DA487EF7BD9">
            <Title>iPAD VERSION</Title>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="DCD37590-FD3D-4DCA-81AA-6B1499C86417">
            <Title>App</Title>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="4AD82828-4A57-475D-8260-8EEDA7FAF043">
            <Title>4. Sync architecture</Title>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="27DF371A-1D12-4899-A7D8-C280F49B0B88">
            <Text>Encryption &amp; key model

Recommended: client-side encryption + split-key recovery
	•	Each document/chunk encrypted with a DEK (data key).
	•	DEKs are wrapped by a KEK (key-encryption key).
	•	KEK is split:
	◦	Part protected on-device (Secure Enclave/Keystore)
	◦	Part stored in cloud KMS/HSM (tenant-isolated)
	•	Decryption requires both parts + authenticated user session.
Why this hybrid key approach is good:
	•	Cloud can store and sync safely (it holds encrypted blobs).
	•	You can still do account recovery / multi-device enrollment.
	•	If a user nukes access, you can do crypto-erasure by destroying wraps.
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="41BB8782-F9A2-437F-B594-DD11DB9B3EBE">
            <Title>10. Concrete end-to-end flows</Title>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="B91BC524-0199-432D-97A8-002E1B006B7A">
            <Title>3. Cloud Storage</Title>
            <Text>Cloud storage: sync without giving the cloud your plaintext (if possible)
Best-practice target: client-side encryption (zero-knowledge style)
	•	Device generates a Data Encryption Key (DEK) per file (or per chunk).
	•	Encrypt file locally → upload encrypted blob to cloud object storage.
	•	Cloud never sees plaintext.
Key management options
	•	User-derived key (passphrase) → you can’t recover accounts easily.
	•	Escrowed keys (recoverable) → more supportable, but higher trust burden.
	•	Split key (recommended compromise):
	◦	Part on device, part in cloud HSM/KMS; requires both to decrypt.
	•	Support multi-device by securely re-wrapping keys for new devices.
Sync
	•	Encrypted files + encrypted metadata
	•	Conflict resolution at metadata layer, not content layer.
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="CBEAC9DC-4E65-47ED-AAB5-E2B8765FB6DB">
            <Text>“Event log” + “CRDT-ish” metadata, not file overwrites
	•	Every change produces an append-only event:
	◦	upload_record, tag_added, note_created, doc_deleted, correction_made
	•	Cloud stores events + encrypted blobs.
	•	Devices replay events to converge state.
	•	Conflicts (e.g., two devices edit the same note) resolve at metadata layer.
This keeps you sane across iOS/Android + web.
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="89CCD311-D1AA-4FCF-AF2B-E039DD129649">
            <Title>2. Data Layers</Title>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="DC5EC25D-2300-4F69-8816-A3FFF0AAF57C">
            <Text>LLM cloud: “minimize exposure” design (RAG + strict controls)
You basically have three patterns:
Pattern 1: “Cloud LLM sees plaintext” (simplest, most risk)
	•	You send chunks of PHI to the LLM API.
	•	Requires extremely strong vendor terms and technical controls.
	•	In HIPAA mode, you’ll need a BAA (and likely a dedicated/isolated setup).
Pattern 2: “De-identify/redact → cloud LLM” (middle ground)
	•	On-device (or in your secure compute), redact identifiers:
	◦	Names, addresses, MRN, phone, DOB (sometimes partial DOB), etc.
	•	Send redacted chunks to LLM.
	•	Keep a local mapping if the user wants rehydrated output.
Caveat: De-identification is hard to guarantee, and “tokenization” isn’t magic if you can reverse it.
Pattern 3 (ideal): “Confidential compute LLM gateway” (best privacy you can buy)
	•	You run an LLM gateway service in a locked-down environment:
	◦	Dedicated VPC
	◦	No persistent logs
	◦	Egress restrictions
	◦	Short-lived request storage only
	•	Optionally use confidential computing (TEEs) so even cloud admins can’t inspect memory easily.
	•	The LLM can be:
	◦	A hosted open-weight model you control
	◦	Or a “private managed” endpoint with strong contractual + technical isolation
This is the enterprise-style “private managed API” approach.
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="2FA80FAB-2F79-4CF6-9F3C-10E3F37175D2">
            <Text>Tier A: On-device synthesis (default for small tasks)
	•	Quick summaries of a single doc, short Q&amp;A, redaction, simple timeline.
Tier B: Secure cloud synthesis (for heavy lift)
	•	Longitudinal timeline across years
	•	Medication reconciliation
	•	Trend analysis on labs
	•	Multi-doc summarization
	•	“Prepare a doctor visit brief”
Key design: Cloud synthesis runs in a policy-enforced AI gateway, not directly from the app to an LLM.
</Text>
        </Document>
